### Sodium Channel Toxins
- Alpha-toxins: slow inactivation
- Beta-toxins: shift activation threshold
- Result: prolonged action potentials
- Repetitive neuronal firing

### Clinical Correlates
- Motor neuron activation: muscle fasciculations
- Autonomic: hypersalivation, tachycardia
- Cranial nerves: opsoclonus, dysphagia
- Respiratory: airway compromise

## Severity Factors
- Age (children > adults)
- Body mass (lower = higher venom dose/kg)
- Species variation
- Amount of venom injected

## Evidence-Based Treatment

### Antivenom (Anascorp)
- Equine F(ab')2 fragments
- Rapidly reverses neurotoxicity
- Reduces ICU admission and sedation needs
- Low adverse reaction rate

### Dosing
- 3 vials IV initially
- Additional vials if symptoms persist
- Most respond within 1-2 hours

### When to Use
- Grade III-IV envenomation
- Age <2 years with any systemic symptoms
- Respiratory compromise

## Discharge Criteria
- Resolution of neurotoxicity
- No respiratory symptoms
- Tolerating oral intake
- Observation 4+ hours for Grade I-II`,
