### Venom Composition
- 50-100 peptide components
- Sodium channel toxins (most clinically relevant)
- Potassium channel toxins
- Phospholipases
- Antimicrobial peptides

### Sodium Channel Toxin Structure
- 60-70 amino acids
- Cysteine-stabilized alpha-helix
- Binding sites on sodium channel
- Alpha-toxins: site 3 (inactivation)
- Beta-toxins: site 4 (activation)

## Evidence Base

### Antivenom Efficacy
- RCT demonstrated rapid symptom reversal
- Reduced midazolam requirements
- Decreased ICU admissions
- Cost-effective for severe cases

### Antivenom Safety
- Acute reactions: ~3%
- Serum sickness: rare
- No fatalities reported
- Safe in pregnancy (limited data)

## Special Populations

### Pediatric Considerations
- Higher risk due to venom:body mass ratio
- Lower threshold for antivenom
- Close monitoring essential
- Consider antivenom for Grade II with rapid progression

### Pregnancy
- Case reports suggest safety
- Fetal monitoring recommended
- Treatment same as non-pregnant

## Global Perspective
- Scorpion envenomation major health issue in Middle East, North Africa
- Different species, different antivenoms
- Fatality rates higher with limited access to care`,
